<subSubSection id="C3106A81903EF400FF78ADF7FC51F95B" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB5390A903EF400FF78ADF7FE0DFAC6" blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FF78ADF7FEC7FD23" box="[199,338,727,750]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Description.</emphasis>
General body shape and colour: elongated but stout body, mottled brown and black or dirty greenish (
<figureCitation id="1331258F903EF400FEB5ADDAFEF5FCDE" box="[266,352,762,787]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1071,1093]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1049]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,193,1050]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 18. Male Apteroscirtus cristatus n. sp., Mazumbai forest reserve in the West Usambara Mountains. Arrows point to keels of abdominal tergites which are conspicuous in this species, but hardly discernible in A. planidorsatus n. sp. from the Uluguru Mountains and thus a good character distinguishing these two Tanzanian species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248338/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="1331258F903EF400FECEADDBFE05FCDE" box="[369,400,763,787]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,995,1017]" captionTargetBox="[225,1401,176,974]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[192,1402,168,974]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Male Apteroscirtus cristatus n. sp., habitus, semilateral view; Mazumbai forest reserve." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248339/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">19</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FE16ADDAFD39FCDE" box="[425,684,762,787]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Head and antennae.—</emphasis>
Antennae more than twice the body length, about 
<quantity id="4CF294EF903EF400FABFADDAFAC2FCDF" box="[1280,1367,762,787]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" unit="cm" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4–5 cm</quantity>
long. Fastigium verticis flat, constricted at height of eyes and widening towards height of antennae (
<figureCitation id="1331258F903EF400FB7EAC3EFA81FCFA" box="[1217,1300,798,823]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[210,1378,1057,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[210,1378,1057,1962]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Morphological details of male Apteroscirtus species. A, B. Fastigium verticis, A. cristatus n. sp. (A) and A. planidorsatus n. sp. (B). C, D. Male abdominal apex, A. cristatus (C) and A. planidorsatus (D)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248340/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FB49AC3FFA81FCFA" box="[1270,1300,799,823]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
A); abruptly forming acute angle to face, meeting fastigium of frons in a shallow horizontal line. 
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FB03AC62FAB8FC96" box="[1212,1325,834,859]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Thorax.—</emphasis>
Pronotum constricted at first sulcus; disk of pronotum flat and smooth with faint median carina. Lateral lobes of pronotum smooth, brown-black marked bordering disk of pronotum. Disk of meso- and metazona of pronotum almost triangular, with slightly undulating posterior margin of pronotum. Sulcus dividing meso- and metazona deep, running almost to lower margin of pronotal lobes. Tegmina tiny rounded lobes, hardly protruding from posterior margin of pronotum. 
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FE3AACD7FE4FFBC3" box="[389,474,1015,1038]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Legs.—</emphasis>
Legs long and slender, base of hind femur stout. 
<collectingCountry id="F31D799A903EF400FC46ACD6FBA4FBC2" box="[1017,1073,1014,1039]" name="India" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Hind</collectingCountry>
femora surpassing apex of body about 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FF62AB3AFE95FBFE" box="[221,256,1050,1075]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times of their length, hind tibiae as long as femora. Tympana of fore tibiae oval and open on both sides. All femora unarmed. Fore and mid tibiae unarmed except for few spines at posterior outer side. 
<collectingCountry id="F31D799A903EF400FB5CAB1EFA8EFB9A" box="[1251,1307,1086,1111]" name="India" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Hind</collectingCountry>
tibiae with double-row of numerous stout spines along dorsal side, and few spines at posterior part on inner sides of hind tibiae. 
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FF5AABA6FEFAFB52" box="[229,367,1158,1183]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Abdomen.—</emphasis>
Abdominal tergites medially with conspicuous keels (
<figureCitation id="1331258F903EF400FC6AABA6FBBFFB52" box="[981,1066,1158,1183]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1071,1093]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1049]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,193,1050]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 18. Male Apteroscirtus cristatus n. sp., Mazumbai forest reserve in the West Usambara Mountains. Arrows point to keels of abdominal tergites which are conspicuous in this species, but hardly discernible in A. planidorsatus n. sp. from the Uluguru Mountains and thus a good character distinguishing these two Tanzanian species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248338/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FBB3ABA7FBBFFB52" box="[1036,1066,1159,1183]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
), elongating posterior margin of tergites. Lateral on abdomen dark brown to black fascia. Cerci stout and of light colour, slightly curved inwardly (
<figureCitation id="1331258F903EF400FF20ABEEFF60FB2A" box="[159,245,1230,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[210,1378,1057,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[210,1378,1057,1962]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Morphological details of male Apteroscirtus species. A, B. Fastigium verticis, A. cristatus n. sp. (A) and A. planidorsatus n. sp. (B). C, D. Male abdominal apex, A. cristatus (C) and A. planidorsatus (D)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248340/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FF69ABEFFF60FB2A" box="[214,245,1231,1255]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
C). Subgenital plate typical for 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4289903EF400FDDDABEFFD6DFB2B" box="[610,760,1231,1254]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FDDDABEFFD6DFB2B" box="[610,760,1231,1254]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Apteroscirtus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, elongate and acute forked at its posterior end (
<figureCitation id="1331258F903EF400FA99ABEEFAE9FB2A" box="[1318,1404,1230,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[210,1378,1057,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[210,1378,1057,1962]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Morphological details of male Apteroscirtus species. A, B. Fastigium verticis, A. cristatus n. sp. (A) and A. planidorsatus n. sp. (B). C, D. Male abdominal apex, A. cristatus (C) and A. planidorsatus (D)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248340/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FAE2ABEFFAE9FB2A" box="[1373,1404,1231,1255]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
C). Styli minute little dots.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB5390A903EF400FF78AA36FC65FABA" blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Female.—Larger than male. No signs of tegmina, thus completely apterous. 
<collectingCountry id="F31D799A903EF400FB95AA36FBF7FAE2" box="[1066,1122,1302,1327]" name="India" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Hind</collectingCountry>
femora very stout and long but only surpassing body about half of their total length. Ovipositor stout and slightly up-curved at posterior part (
<figureCitation id="1331258F903EF400FF20AA7EFF64FABA" box="[159,241,1374,1399]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1995,2017]" captionTargetBox="[172,1432,977,1942]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[154,1433,977,1972]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 21. Ovipositors of Apteroscirtus species. A. A. cristatus n. sp. B. A. planidorsatus n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248341/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FF6BAA7FFF64FABA" box="[212,241,1375,1399]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Subgenital plate broad with straight posterior margin (
<figureCitation id="1331258F903EF400FCC5AA7EFC58FABA" box="[890,973,1374,1399]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="32.[151,250,731,753]" captionTargetBox="[150,1434,207,691]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[149,1434,207,691]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 22. Subgenital plates of female Apteroscirtus species. A. A. cristatus n. sp. B. A. planidorsatus n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248342/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FC10AA7FFC58FABA" box="[943,973,1375,1399]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
A).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB5390A903EF400FF78AAA4FF71FA72" blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FF78AAA4FEE5FA56" box="[199,368,1412,1435]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Measurements,</emphasis>
males (mm) (N = 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FDF8AAA3FDCDFA56" box="[583,600,1411,1435]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="4.0">4</number>
). Body length 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FCBDAAA2FCDEFA56" box="[770,843,1410,1435]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="18.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="16.0">16–20</number>
. Length of pronotum 6.0– 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FBC7AAA2FB0EFA56" box="[1144,1179,1410,1435]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="6.5">6.5</number>
. Length of hind femur 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FF28AA87FF74FA72" box="[151,225,1447,1471]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="25.5" valueMax="27.0" valueMin="24.0">24–27</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB5390A903EF400FF78AAECFD91F9CA" blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FF78AAECFEE5FA2E" box="[199,368,1484,1507]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Measurements,</emphasis>
females (mm) (N = 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FDE9AAEBFDF2FA2E" box="[598,615,1483,1507]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="4.0">4</number>
). Body length 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FCB3AAEBFCC0FA2E" box="[780,853,1483,1507]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="23.5" valueMax="27.0" valueMin="20.0">20–27</number>
. Length of pronotum 7.0– 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FBC2AAEBFB34FA2E" box="[1149,1185,1483,1507]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="7.2">7.2</number>
. Length of hind femur 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FF28AACFFF74F9CA" box="[151,225,1519,1543]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="29.0" valueMax="31.0" valueMin="27.0">27–31</number>
. Ovipositor length 
<number id="3DC22B2D903EF400FE09AACEFD95F9CA" box="[438,512,1518,1543]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="18.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="16.0">16–20</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB5390A903EF400FF78A932FC51F95B" blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Diagnosis.— 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4289903EF400FEE5A933FE4EF9E6" box="[346,475,1555,1579]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cristatus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FEE5A933FE4EF9E6" box="[346,475,1555,1579]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">A. cristatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5863903EF400FE5DA933FD8AF9E7" box="[482,543,1555,1578]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be separated easily from other members of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4289903EF400FBFCA933FB4CF9E7" box="[1091,1241,1555,1578]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FBFCA933FB4CF9E7" box="[1091,1241,1555,1578]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Apteroscirtus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the elongated keels on the adominal tergites. The abdomen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4289903EF400FD76A917FCCBF982" box="[713,862,1590,1615]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denudatus">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FD76A917FCCBF982" box="[713,862,1590,1615]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">A. denudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is completely smooth, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4289903EF400FBD1A917FAF8F982" authority="Rehn" authorityName="Rehn" box="[1134,1389,1590,1615]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruwenzoricus">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FBD1A917FABDF983" box="[1134,1320,1591,1614]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">A. ruwenzoricus</emphasis>
Rehn
</taxonomicName>
has week keels and also 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4289903EF400FEC0A97BFDACF9BE" box="[383,569,1626,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="planidorsatus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FEC0A97BFDACF9BE" box="[383,569,1626,1651]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">A. planidorsatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5863903EF400FDFFA97BFDE8F9BF" box="[576,637,1627,1650]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has smooth abdominal tergites. 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4289903EF400FC56A97BFB59F9BE" authority="Karsch" authorityName="Karsch" box="[1001,1228,1626,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inalatus">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FC56A97BFBF6F9BE" box="[1001,1123,1626,1651]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">A. inalatus</emphasis>
(Karsch)
</taxonomicName>
has rounded wing lobes, an unique character among the described species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4289903EF400FC98A95FFC28F95B" box="[807,957,1663,1686]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FC98A95FFC28F95B" box="[807,957,1663,1686]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Apteroscirtus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3106A81903EF400FF78A983FAC6F976" box="[199,1363,1698,1723]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB5390A903EF400FF78A983FAC6F976" blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" box="[199,1363,1698,1723]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FF78A983FEDBF976" bold="true" box="[199,334,1699,1723]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Etymology.</emphasis>
– lat. 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4289903EF400FE2CA984FE61F976" box="[403,500,1700,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cristatus">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FE2CA984FE61F976" box="[403,500,1700,1723]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">cristatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
= crest, because of the pronounced abdominal keels medially on the tergites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3106A81903EF400FF78A9E6FCB5F8EA" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BB5390A903EF400FF78A9E6FBB2F912" blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" box="[199,1063,1734,1759]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FF78A9E6FECCF912" bold="true" box="[199,345,1734,1759]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Distribution</emphasis>
: 
<collectingCountry id="F31D799A903EF400FED7A9E6FE45F912" box="[360,464,1734,1759]" name="Tanzania" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, probably endemic to the West Usambara Mountains.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB5390A903EF400FF78A9CBFCB5F8EA" blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FF78A9CBFE3AF8CE" bold="true" box="[199,431,1770,1795]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Ecology &amp; Biology</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A4289903EF400FE7CA9CBFDD2F8CE" box="[451,583,1771,1795]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cristatus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FE7CA9CBFDD2F8CE" box="[451,583,1771,1795]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">A. cristatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5863903EF400FDEBA9CBFD00F8CF" box="[596,661,1771,1794]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is an inhabitant of leaf litter on the forest floor where it is well camouflaged. It escapes with large jumps when disturbed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3106A81903EF400FF78A812FC12F887" box="[199,903,1842,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB5390A903EF400FF78A812FC12F887" blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" box="[199,903,1842,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis id="B97EE518903EF400FF78A812FEB6F886" bold="true" box="[199,291,1842,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Habitat</emphasis>
: Montane forest, recorded from around 
<quantity id="4CF294EF903EF400FD5AA812FC16F887" box="[741,899,1842,1867]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" unit="m" value="1650.0" valueMax="1800.0" valueMin="1500.0">1500–1800 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
